ch could cause subtle bugs in carry-forward computation.\n\n- **`TestPostCommit_IdleSession_NoTranscriptFallbackForCarryForward`** is a well-structured regression test. It sets up the exact edge case (IDLE session with empty `FilesTouched` but a transcript that WOULD match committed files) and verifies that condensation does not happen. The comment clearly documents what regression it prevents.\n\n- **Existing integration-level tests** (`TestSessionHasNewContentFromLiveTranscript_NormalizesAbsolutePaths`, `TestSessionHasNewContentFromLiveTranscript_IncludesSubagentFiles`, `TestPostCommit_IdleSession_SkipsSentinelWait`) continue to exercise the refactored call sites end-to-end, providing confidence that the refactoring preserves behavior.\n\n- The test naming follows the project's `TestComponent_Scenario` convention consistently.\n\n- The doc comments on both `resolveFilesTouched` and `hasNewTranscriptWork` clearly document the \"all call sites that need X should use this\" consolidation intent, which helps prevent future callers from bypassing these entry points.</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>78576</total_tokens><tool_uses>23</tool_uses><duration_ms>128759</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-alex-workspace-cli--worktrees-2/tasks/aeb2d5be288339ce9.output\n\n---\n\n<task-notification>\n<task-id>a9d0176b7a0a7fd4a</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>toolu_01PcqdJ2GDdA6ZqtNxbp8Lq2</tool-use-id>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Error handling review\" completed</summary>\n<result>I now have a complete picture. Let me compile the error handling audit.\n\n---\n\n## Error Handling Audit: PR #597 (`refactoring-transcript-reads`)\n\nThis PR consolidates transcript file extraction behind two new functions (`resolveFilesTouched` and `hasNewTranscriptWork`) and introduces `prepareTranscriptForState` as a convenience wrapper. While the refactoring is a good consolidation, I found several error handling concerns that range from medium to high severity.\n\n---\n\n### ISSUE 1: `prepareTranscriptForState` silently discards `GetByAgentType` errors\n\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/2/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/common.go`, lines 1430-1439\n\n**Severity:** HIGH\n\n**Code:**\n```go\nfunc prepareTranscriptForState(ctx context.Context, state *SessionState) {\n\tif !state.Phase.IsActive() || state.TranscriptPath == \"\" || state.AgentType == \"\" {\n\t\treturn\n\t}\n\tag, err := agent.GetByAgentType(state.AgentType)\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\treturn  // <--- Silent return, no logging\n\t}\n\tprepareTranscriptIfNeeded(ctx, ag, state.TranscriptPath)\n}\n```\n\n**Issue Description:** When `GetByAgentType` fails -- which happens when the agent type stored in session state does not match any registered agent (e.g., data corruption, agent plugin removed, or a future agent type from a newer CLI version) -- this function silently returns with no logging whatsoever. The caller (`resolveFilesTouched`) will then proceed to call `extractModifiedFilesFromLiveTranscript`, which will also call `GetByAgentType`, fail again silently, and return `nil`. The result: `resolveFilesTouched` returns an empty file list with no indication that anything went wrong.\n\nCompare this to `hasNewTranscriptWork` at line 1406-1408, which has the exact same silent `return false` for `GetByAgentType` errors but at least has a documented rationale in its doc comment (lines 1395-1398). `prepareTranscriptForState` has no such rationale.\n\n**Hidden Errors:**\n- Unknown/corrupted agent type in session state\n- Registry initialization race condition (unlikely but possible)\n- Agent plugin removed between sessions\n\n**User Impact:** If an agent type becomes unrecognized (e.g., user downgrades CLI version), transcript preparation silently fails. The subsequent transcript extraction also fails silently. The user's checkpoint ends up with empty `FilesTouched`, which means carry-forward computation produces no files, and the user loses track of which files the agent modified. There is zero feedback about why this happened.\n\n**Recommendation:** Add a `logging.Debug` call when `GetByAgentType` fails, consistent with how `hasNewTranscriptWork` logs `PrepareTranscript` failures. This function is called from hot paths (hooks), so Debug-level is appropriate:\n\n```go\nfunc prepareTranscriptForState(ctx context.Context, state *SessionState) {\n\tif !state.Phase.IsActive() || state.TranscriptPath == \"\" || state.AgentType == \"\" {\n\t\treturn\n\t}\n\tag, err := agent.GetByAgentType(state.AgentType)\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\tlogging.Debug(ctx, \"prepareTranscriptForState: unknown agent type\",\n\t\t\tslog.String(\"session_id\", state.SessionID),\n\t\t\tslog.String(\"agent_type\", string(state.AgentType)),\n\t\t\tslog.Any(\"error\", err),\n\t\t)\n\t\treturn\n\t}\n\tprepareTranscriptIfNeeded(ctx, ag, state.TranscriptPath)\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### ISSUE 2: `hasNewTranscriptWork` silently returns `false` for `GetTranscriptPosition` failures -- behavioral change from the old code\n\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/2/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_hooks.go`, lines 1432-1434\n\n**Severity:** HIGH\n\n**Code (new):**\n```go\ncurrentPos, err := analyzer.GetTranscriptPosition(state.TranscriptPath)\nif err != nil {\n\treturn false  // <--- Silent return false, no logging\n}\n```\n\n**Issue Description:** The doc comment (lines 1395-1398) claims this is \"intentional fail-safe behavior\" where `false` means \"no new work detected, which conservatively skips condensation on errors.\" However, the comment mischaracterizes the safety properties.\n\nReturning `false` when `GetTranscriptPosition` fails does NOT \"conservatively skip condensation.\" It **prevents** condensation from happening, which means the user's checkpoint data is **lost** -- the opposite of conservative. If the transcript file is temporarily unreadable (permissions, transient I/O error, NFS hiccup), the