ID),\n\t\tslog.String(\"transcript_path\", state.TranscriptPath),\n\t\tslog.Any(\"error\", err),\n\t)\n\treturn false\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### ISSUE 3: `hasNewTranscriptWork` silently returns `false` when agent does not implement `TranscriptAnalyzer`\n\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/2/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_hooks.go`, lines 1427-1430\n\n**Severity:** MEDIUM\n\n**Code:**\n```go\nanalyzer, ok := ag.(agent.TranscriptAnalyzer)\nif !ok {\n\treturn false\n}\n```\n\n**Issue Description:** If an agent does not implement the `TranscriptAnalyzer` interface, `hasNewTranscriptWork` returns `false` (no new work), but `sessionHasNewContentFromLiveTranscript` still proceeds to call `extractModifiedFilesFromLiveTranscript` which performs the same type assertion at lines 1467-1470 and also returns `nil`. So if an agent does not implement `TranscriptAnalyzer`, the entire check returns `(false, nil)` and the commit proceeds without a checkpoint trailer.\n\nThis is a pre-existing pattern (the old code did the same thing), but the doc comment's claim that this is documented is only partially true. The comment says \"Returns false if: ... agent doesn't implement TranscriptAnalyzer\" but does not explain the consequence: the user's commit will have no checkpoint metadata for this session.\n\nFor currently registered agents this should not happen (they all implement the interface). But if a new agent is added that does not implement `TranscriptAnalyzer`, this would silently drop checkpoint data with no warning.\n\n**Recommendation:** No code change strictly needed, but adding a `logging.Debug` for this case would help future debugging:\n\n```go\nanalyzer, ok := ag.(agent.TranscriptAnalyzer)\nif !ok {\n\tlogging.Debug(logCtx, \"hasNewTranscriptWork: agent does not implement TranscriptAnalyzer\",\n\t\tslog.String(\"session_id\", state.SessionID),\n\t\tslog.String(\"agent_type\", string(state.AgentType)),\n\t)\n\treturn false\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### ISSUE 4: `sessionHasNewContentFromLiveTranscript` changed semantics -- `hasNewTranscriptWork` returning `false` now conflates \"no new work\" with \"error checking\"\n\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/2/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_hooks.go`, lines 1336-1338\n\n**Severity:** HIGH\n\n**Code (new):**\n```go\nif !s.hasNewTranscriptWork(ctx, state) {\n\treturn false, nil\n}\n```\n\n**Code (old):**\n```go\nmodifiedFiles, ok := s.extractNewModifiedFilesFromLiveTranscript(ctx, state)\nif !ok || len(modifiedFiles) == 0 {\n\treturn false, nil\n}\n```\n\n**Issue Description:** This is the most significant behavioral change in the PR. The old `extractNewModifiedFilesFromLiveTranscript` returned a `([]string, bool)` tuple where the `bool` distinguished between \"extraction succeeded but found nothing\" (`nil, true`) and \"extraction failed\" (`nil, false`). Both cases were treated identically by the caller (`return false, nil`), so the distinction was not used -- but the *information* was available for future use.\n\nThe new `hasNewTranscriptWork` collapses these into a single `bool` return. This means the caller `sessionHasNewContentFromLiveTranscript` now returns `(false, nil)` for ALL of these scenarios:\n1. No transcript path (expected for some sessions)\n2. Unknown agent type (data corruption)\n3. `PrepareTranscript` failed (I/O error) -- execution continues despite this, then `GetTranscriptPosition` may also fail\n4. Agent does not implement `TranscriptAnalyzer` (agent bug)\n5. `GetTranscriptPosition` failed (I/O error)\n6. Transcript position has not advanced (legitimately no new work)\n\nThe function signature `(bool, error)` is misleading because `sessionHasNewContentFromLiveTranscript` **never returns an error** -- the `error` return is always `nil`. Every failure path returns `(false, nil)`. This means the caller at line 888-896:\n```go\nhasNew, contentErr = s.sessionHasNewContent(ctx, repo, state, contentCheckOpts{shadowTree: shadowTree})\nif contentErr != nil {\n\thasNew = true  // err-on-the-side-of-caution fallback\n}\n```\n...will NEVER trigger its safety fallback (`hasNew = true`) for live transcript errors, because errors from `hasNewTranscriptWork` are never surfaced as Go errors. The fail-safe \"assume new content on error\" at line 889-896 is completely bypassed for the live transcript path.\n\n**User Impact:** Same as Issue 2 -- silent data loss on transient errors. The safety net that exists for other error paths (line 889-896) is unreachable for these errors.\n\n**Recommendation:** Consider having `hasNewTranscriptWork` return `(bool, error)` to preserve the ability to distinguish \"definitely no new work\" from \"could not determine.\" Alternatively, keep the current design but make the doc comment on `sessionHasNewContentFromLiveTranscript` explicit that errors in the live transcript path are handled as \"no new work\" rather than triggering the safety fallback. At minimum, ensure all error paths in `hasNewTranscriptWork` are logged (see Issues 2 and 3).\n\n---\n\n### ISSUE 5: `extractModifiedFilesFromLiveTranscript` no longer has PrepareTranscript -- relies on caller contract with no enforcement\n\n**Location:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/2/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_hooks.go`, lines 1449-1455\n\n**Severity:** MEDIUM\n\n**Code:**\n```go\n// extractModifiedFilesFromLiveTranscript extracts modified files from the live transcript\n// (including subagent transcripts) starting from the given offset, and normalizes them\n// to repo-relative paths. Returns the normalized file list.\n//\n// Callers must ensure the transcript is prepared (e.g., via prepareTranscriptForState\n// or hasNewTranscriptWork) before calling this function.\nfunc (s *ManualCommitStrategy) extractModifiedFilesFromLiveTranscript(...)\n```\n\n**Issue Description:** The old code called `PrepareTranscript` inside `extractModifiedFilesFromLiveTranscript` itself, making it self-contained. The new code removes that