``\n\n**Issue Description:** `extractSessionDataFromLiveTranscript` is called during condensation. The function `resolveFilesTouched` calls `prepareTranscriptForState`, which checks `state.Phase.IsActive()` and returns immediately for IDLE/ENDED sessions. However, condensation can happen for IDLE sessions (the `IDLE + GitCommit -> IDLE` transition triggers `ActionCondense`).\n\nIf an IDLE session has empty `FilesTouched` and the transcript needs preparation (OpenCode), `prepareTranscriptForState` will skip preparation because the session is IDLE. Then `extractModifiedFilesFromLiveTranscript` will try to read the transcript, which may not exist or be stale.\n\nFor the IDLE case, the doc comment on `prepareTranscriptForState` says \"IDLE/ENDED sessions are already flushed\" (line 1427). This is true for Claude Code (which writes transcripts continuously) but the assumption relies on the Stop hook having called `PrepareTranscript` -- if the Stop hook failed or was interrupted for OpenCode, the transcript may not have been flushed.\n\nThis is a pre-existing concern (the old `extractModifiedFilesFromLiveTranscript` had the same `Phase.IsActive()` guard), so the PR does not introduce a regression. But the refactoring makes this assumption more fragile because it is now in a different function (`prepareTranscriptForState`) separated from the code that relies on it.\n\n**User Impact:** For OpenCode only, if the Stop hook fails to flush the transcript, IDLE session condensation would use stale transcript data and produce an incomplete files-touched list.\n\n**Recommendation:** No code change required -- the assumption is documented and reasonable. But consider adding a logging statement in `prepareTranscriptForState` when it skips a non-ACTIVE session that has an empty `FilesTouched`, since that is the edge case where skipping preparation matters most.\n\n---\n\n### Positive Observations\n\n1. **The PostCommit carry-forward path (lines 903-909) correctly gates transcript ext